hat nostalgic life of the first postwar decades is being swept aside by radical forces from the Lubavitcher at one end to Reform and feminism at the other. What started in 1945 as a "remnant" community has become a dynamic new center of Jewish life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aHolocaust survivorsxGermany. 0aHolocaust survivorszGermany. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xInfluence. 0aJewish refugeesxHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aJewish refugeeszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewsxHistoryx1945-1990xGermany. 0aJewszGermanyxHistoryy1945-1990. 0aJews, East EuropeanxHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aJews, East EuropeanzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300133127423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300133127.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles